00:02:01.880 --> 00:02:06.160
But even the best reasons do not have to be intuitive or expected by the users.

00:02:06.500 --> 00:02:13.540
Let's take a short trip through how Python package index handles removals and how we can lock the ghost in a uv lock file.

00:02:13.760 --> 00:02:14.120
Forever.

00:02:14.700 --> 00:02:14.980
Forever.

00:02:14.980 --> 00:02:25.240
So this is a security thing, and it's specifically, uniquely an issue for uv and the uv lock file in particular.

00:02:25.400 --> 00:02:33.600
So if you're using uv like I do with like uv pip compile, uv and then requirements.txt, that kind of thing, doesn't apply.

00:02:33.880 --> 00:02:34.760
UV.lock file.

00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:40.700
We're both huge fans of uv, but this, and one of the reasons we are fans is because of the performance, right?

00:02:40.960 --> 00:02:43.940
It's so fast and it bundles so many tools together.

00:02:43.940 --> 00:02:47.300
Some of these are making really interesting tradeoffs.

00:02:47.740 --> 00:02:52.320
Often those tradeoffs are certainly fine, you know, like a short caching period.

00:02:52.420 --> 00:02:59.640
So if you ask it to install something and it did it 10 seconds ago, it's not going to go and ask the APIs for it again and that sort of thing.

00:02:59.920 --> 00:03:03.520
Or uv Python install, which is awesome.

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:06.980
It gets you Python in a couple of seconds instead of forever with a bunch of buttons.

00:03:07.300 --> 00:03:10.520
You know, next, next, next, confirm, agree, confirm, next, next, yes.

00:03:10.740 --> 00:03:12.320
You know, like that installer experience.

00:03:12.320 --> 00:03:18.320
So those are all good, but I guess this is a bit of a negative consequence of having some of these optimizations.

00:03:19.300 --> 00:03:21.000
So I pulled out some, I'll read my notes here.

00:03:21.280 --> 00:03:29.240
So the essence is in the uv lock file, it points directly to the final file on the CDN, I'm guessing.

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:30.200
Or even the storage.

00:03:30.360 --> 00:03:35.980
But, you know, even if you remove something from the storage, it doesn't necessarily remove it from the CDN fastly and so on, right?

00:03:35.980 --> 00:03:39.860
So, however it is, it points to the very final file.

00:03:40.300 --> 00:03:44.420
In, when something is yanked or removed from PyPI, it goes out of the listing.

00:03:44.780 --> 00:03:45.560
You can't find it.

00:03:45.640 --> 00:03:46.740
You ask pip to install it.

00:03:46.800 --> 00:03:47.340
It's not there.

00:03:47.440 --> 00:03:50.660
But the underlying file is still hanging around.

00:03:50.800 --> 00:03:57.700
So if you have a direct URL to the result file, instead of following the redirects or whatever, that file doesn't necessarily get removed.

00:03:57.960 --> 00:03:59.420
That's what that opening was about, right?

00:03:59.420 --> 00:04:01.460
So that's basically the problem.

00:04:01.660 --> 00:04:05.880
If the file is still there, the file is still there, even if it gets yanked, right?

00:04:05.940 --> 00:04:08.300
So there's a couple of interesting knock-on effects.

00:04:08.760 --> 00:04:13.640
So uv lock uniquely preserves this, these ghost packages, they call them in this file.

00:04:13.780 --> 00:04:17.600
So instead of removing them, they just link directly to them as an optimization, I presume.

00:04:17.960 --> 00:04:24.040
However, no other thing like hatch or PDM or whatever links to them, right?

00:04:24.100 --> 00:04:25.640
So they don't do that, right?

00:04:25.640 --> 00:04:27.080
This is specifically about uv.

00:04:27.080 --> 00:04:29.900
So it creates an interesting supply chain problem.

00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:34.940
I mean, that's just like the security problem du jour or de year, right?

00:04:35.100 --> 00:04:36.440
Whatever, year and fridges.

00:04:37.080 --> 00:04:41.720
The problem, all these things are getting some level of takeover.

00:04:42.160 --> 00:04:48.320
And then, you know, that's flowing into packages and other libraries that are built into code.

00:04:48.420 --> 00:04:50.560
And then obviously that amplifies them massively.

00:04:50.900 --> 00:04:56.700
So in this case, an attacker could upload a malicious package and then immediately remove it.

00:04:56.700 --> 00:04:59.900
But still have the uv lock file point at it.

00:05:00.180 --> 00:05:00.280
Okay?

00:05:00.360 --> 00:05:00.580
Yeah.

00:05:00.780 --> 00:05:05.500
So if you immediately remove it, you might outrun the scanners.

00:05:05.760 --> 00:05:11.120
The automated scanners that go, let me scan the new inbound PyPI packages.

00:05:11.320 --> 00:05:12.680
Because that package doesn't exist anymore.

00:05:12.740 --> 00:05:13.600
We don't need to scan it.

00:05:13.600 --> 00:05:19.940
But you could craft a specific uv lock file that still points to the ghosted remnant.

00:05:20.060 --> 00:05:20.540
You know what I mean?

00:05:21.300 --> 00:05:21.420
Yeah.

00:05:21.500 --> 00:05:23.940
But aren't the lock files on the client side?

00:05:24.040 --> 00:05:27.980
So it would be just people that created the client lock files during the...

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:29.500
Yes, that seems possible.

00:05:29.500 --> 00:05:30.440
But imagine this.

00:05:30.540 --> 00:05:37.420
I create Molting Claw or whatever, like the world's third most popular GitHub project out there.

00:05:37.680 --> 00:05:38.260
Put it up.

00:05:38.500 --> 00:05:39.540
Get it working normally.

00:05:39.540 --> 00:05:44.220
And then after it gets really popular, I update a lock file.

00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:45.440
Not even the input.

00:05:45.580 --> 00:05:46.880
Not the PyProject.tom or nothing.

00:05:46.880 --> 00:05:54.280
I just update the lock file itself to point at this ghosted malicious file.

00:05:54.600 --> 00:05:57.840
So anybody who installs it, well, they uv sync.

00:05:58.020 --> 00:06:00.940
That installs everything in the lock file and off it goes.

00:06:00.940 --> 00:06:05.280
So it's not that you ran and installed the thing.

00:06:05.600 --> 00:06:15.540
It's that somebody could craft a lock file such that if you sync that project, then it's installed onto your machine and off to its regular badness, you know, with it set up.py or whatever.

00:06:15.540 --> 00:06:16.920
So beware, folks.

00:06:17.420 --> 00:06:17.660
Beware.

00:06:17.740 --> 00:06:21.500
I'm not sure exactly what the solution here is, but it's something that could happen.

00:06:21.560 --> 00:06:26.080
And maybe the Astral team, I'm sure the Astral team has already heard about this.

00:06:26.140 --> 00:06:27.140
This was from last week.

00:06:27.260 --> 00:06:27.480
Okay.

00:06:27.780 --> 00:06:28.160
Interesting.

00:06:28.500 --> 00:06:30.540
Well, we'll wait to hear back.

00:06:31.040 --> 00:06:31.240
Yeah.

00:06:31.280 --> 00:06:32.080
I haven't heard anything.

00:06:32.240 --> 00:06:34.920
I mean, I guess if I go to the end, there's not like an update.

