00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:32.080
It's a little...

00:09:32.080 --> 00:09:39.660
It apparently works great on macOS, Linux, and WSL2 uses bubble wrap.

00:09:39.660 --> 00:09:46.340
So if you're using WSL2 for Cloud Cursor or Claude Code, that might be okay.

00:09:46.340 --> 00:09:48.540
But what about other agents and stuff?

00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:54.060
So what we got a suggestion was that Claude Code has this built in.

00:09:54.920 --> 00:09:55.760
We're not...

00:09:55.760 --> 00:10:00.140
I'm not sure how well if it's really restricted or if it's suggestions.

00:10:00.860 --> 00:10:01.260
Anyway.

00:10:01.700 --> 00:10:02.740
I haven't tried it out.

00:10:02.940 --> 00:10:06.420
So I'd love to hear what other people think about the sandboxing stuff.

00:10:06.640 --> 00:10:14.780
Anyway, the same kind of idea that Claude Code uses is pulled out as something else you can use with different AI agents if you want.

00:10:14.780 --> 00:10:16.820
So this is a project called Fence.

00:10:17.360 --> 00:10:20.140
It's lightweight sandboxes for terminal agents.

00:10:20.140 --> 00:10:23.800
And it uses this similar sort of stuff that Claude Code does.

00:10:24.180 --> 00:10:32.000
And this is pretty exciting to be able to restrict what it has access to, like file permissions.

00:10:32.180 --> 00:10:35.720
You can restrict how much your file system it has access to.

00:10:35.940 --> 00:10:42.780
You can restrict the network access, which websites and stuff it can access.

00:10:42.780 --> 00:10:47.700
And even GitHub repos, restrict which repos.

00:10:48.120 --> 00:10:49.060
That's all cool.

00:10:49.300 --> 00:10:51.520
And it's also really cool that this is open source.

00:10:51.720 --> 00:10:58.080
So this is Go code, but it's a fence project that people can contribute to.

00:10:58.220 --> 00:11:00.000
And it's very active right now.

00:11:00.180 --> 00:11:06.840
So I'd be excited to hear what other people think of fencing, if you think it's safe enough.

00:11:07.500 --> 00:11:07.740
Anyway.

00:11:07.740 --> 00:11:08.000
Okay.

