00:11:39.820 --> 00:11:41.160
I think this is a neat idea.

00:11:41.400 --> 00:11:42.640
I like that it's open source.

00:11:42.840 --> 00:11:54.860
The one thing I don't like, and I don't know that there's necessarily a great fix for that, just given the way that it works, is it seems like you can have it work on any terminal command, right?

00:11:54.920 --> 00:11:59.340
So like Claude Code or Codex, CLI or Gemini CLI, whatever.

00:11:59.720 --> 00:12:09.640
But say VS Code, Cursor, PyCharm, you want to run one of those, but have the agents that run in those more proper editors limited?

00:12:10.020 --> 00:12:11.320
That seems harder, you know?

00:12:11.480 --> 00:12:12.620
It doesn't seem like it supports that.

00:12:12.860 --> 00:12:13.000
Yeah.

00:12:13.300 --> 00:12:15.320
So that's the way I like to work.

00:12:15.460 --> 00:12:26.820
Honestly, this might be a minority opinion, but I think Claude Code and Friends, the way that they work are an anti-pattern for how real software developers should be coding.

00:12:27.160 --> 00:12:37.400
And what I mean by that is Claude Code and other CLI ones encourage you to just have the code just like rip by, like do this and it's just like, you see the code screaming by and it's like, okay, I'm done.

00:12:37.660 --> 00:12:42.920
And then your job is to like, accept that or whatever, or you wait 10 minutes for it to do a thing.

00:12:43.040 --> 00:12:44.880
I was doing a project a few days ago.

00:12:45.080 --> 00:12:50.120
Claude Code spun up five agents that all ran for 15 minutes in parallel.

00:12:50.120 --> 00:12:51.680
And then it gave me the result.

00:12:52.000 --> 00:12:53.960
So that's a lot of code changes.

00:12:54.600 --> 00:13:01.060
And that's a lot of my credits in addition to just time to wait 15 minutes and see how it came out.

00:13:01.260 --> 00:13:07.380
So what I much prefer is to have some kind of editor, VS Code, PyCharm, whatever, where the work is happening.

00:13:07.380 --> 00:13:11.700
And as it's making changes, I can roll up, okay, made this change.

00:13:11.740 --> 00:13:12.020
Let me look.

00:13:12.100 --> 00:13:13.280
Actually, it's going down the wrong path.

00:13:13.300 --> 00:13:14.000
Hey, stop, stop, stop.

00:13:14.080 --> 00:13:14.820
No, don't look.

00:13:14.840 --> 00:13:15.540
You did this wrong.

00:13:15.680 --> 00:13:16.420
Go that way.

00:13:16.720 --> 00:13:18.460
You know, you're not following the patterns of this.

00:13:18.460 --> 00:13:25.220
So with the just like streaming by like a social media feed, it encourages you not to review it while it's working.

00:13:25.460 --> 00:13:27.180
And I think that that is not right.

00:13:27.240 --> 00:13:32.660
I know the trend is to like not review code at all, but there's the trend is also to get a bunch of like unstable software.

00:13:32.820 --> 00:13:33.540
So thank you.

00:13:33.900 --> 00:13:36.640
Anyway, I don't like the CLI ones because of that.

00:13:36.880 --> 00:13:39.980
Therefore, I probably won't be using this, but I would like to.

00:13:40.260 --> 00:13:40.680
That's my take.

